HEADWORD: Mythology
<hw>My*thol"o*gy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Mythologies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[F.
<ets>mythologie</ets>, L. <ets>mythologia</ets>, Gr.
<grk>myqologi`a</grk>; <grk>my^qos</grk>, fable, myth +
<grk>lo`gos</grk> speech, discourse.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The science
which treats of myths; a treatise on myths.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A body of myths; esp., the collective myths which
describe the gods of a heathen people; <as>as, the <ex>mythology</ex> of
the Greeks</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mythoplasm</ent>⟦br⟧
